    {
      "title": "3. How Stress Changes Meaning",
      "subtopics": [
        {
          "title": "3.1. Noun vs. Verb Stress: Same Word, Different Meaning",
          "sections": [
            {
              "text": "Some words in English can be both a noun (a thing) and a verb (an action). The meaning changes depending on where you put the stress. If the stress is on the first syllable, it's usually a noun. If the stress is on the second syllable, it's usually a verb.",
              "examples": [
                {
                  "label": "Present (Noun)",
                  "value": "PRE-sent (a gift)"
                },
                {
                  "label": "Present (Verb)",
                  "value": "pre-SENT (to give or show)"
                },
                {
                  "label": "Record (Noun)",
                  "value": "RE-cord (a piece of information or music)"
                },
                {
                  "label": "Record (Verb)",
                  "value": "re-CORD (to write down or save sound)"
                },
                {
                  "label": "Object (Noun)",
                  "value": "OB-ject (a thing)"
                },
                {
                  "label": "Object (Verb)",
                  "value": "ob-JECT (to disagree)"
                },
                {
                  "label": "Conduct (Noun)",
                  "value": "CON-duct (behavior)"
                },
                {
                  "label": "Conduct (Verb)",
                  "value": "con-DUCT (to lead or manage)"
                },
                {
                  "label": "Rebel (Noun)",
                  "value": "RE-bel (a person who fights against authority)"
                },
                {
                  "label": "Rebel (Verb)",
                  "value": "re-BEL (to fight against authority)"
                },
                {
                  "label": "Increase (Noun)",
                  "value": "IN-crease (a rise in number or amount)"
                },
                {
                  "label": "Increase (Verb)",
                  "value": "in-CREASE (to make bigger or more)"
                },
                {
                  "label": "Protest (Noun)",
                  "value": "PRO-test (a statement or action expressing disapproval)"
                },
                {
                  "label": "Protest (Verb)",
                  "value": "pro-TEST (to express an objection to something)"
                }
              ],
              "usage_examples": [
                "My friend gave me a nice PRE-sent.",
                "I will pre-SENT my work tomorrow.",
                "Keep a RE-cord of your attendance.",
                "Please re-CORD the song.",
                "What is that OB-ject on the table?",
                "I ob-JECT to your idea.",
                "His CON-duct was very good.",
                "She will con-DUCT the meeting.",
                "The RE-bel fought for freedom.",
                "They decided to re-BEL against the rules.",
                "There was an IN-crease in rainfall this year.",
                "We need to in-CREASE our efforts.",
                "The farmers held a PRO-test.",
                "They will pro-TEST the new law.",
                "This is a DE-sert (dry land). They will de-SERT (abandon) the village."
              ],
